Spring Boot
* A project built on top of Spring to simplify development.
* Provides:
    * Auto-configuration
    * Starter dependencies
    * Embedded servers (Tomcat, Jetty, Netty)
* Eliminates most manual configuration.
* Reduces development time; developers focus on business logic, not setup.

✅ What is Dependency Injection (DI)?
Dependency Injection is a design pattern where an object receives its dependencies from an external source instead of creating them itself.
Benefits
* Loose coupling
* Easy testing
* Better maintainability
Types of DI
* Constructor Injection (recommended)
* Field Injection
* Setter Injection

✅ What is Inversion of Control (IoC)?
IoC is a principle where the control of object creation is handed over to the framework, not the application code.
Relation to DI
* IoC is the principle
* Dependency Injection is the technique that implements IoC

✅ What Happens When a Spring Boot Application Starts?
* The main method calls SpringApplication.run().
* Spring Boot:
    * Performs auto-configuration
    * Scans for components
    * Creates and initializes the Spring ApplicationContext
    * Instantiates all beans
    * Starts the embedded server (Tomcat/Jetty/Netty)
    * Application becomes ready to accept requests

✅ What is a Bean? Explain Bean Lifecycle
A Bean is an object created and managed by the Spring IoC Container.
Bean Lifecycle
1. Bean definition loaded (using annotations or XML)
2. Bean instantiation (via constructor)
3. Dependency Injection
4. BeanPostProcessor hooks (before & after initialization)
5. Bean ready for use
6. Destruction when context shuts down
Types of Bean Scopes
* Singleton (default, one instance)
* Prototype (new instance every time)
* Request (per HTTP request)
* Session (per session)
* Global Session (portlet applications)

